    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-01-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-01-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="269"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d269">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72112/2200¾</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to President
                            <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-01-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 24, 1916</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I enclose a confidential
                    telegram received from Ambassador Page at London,<note n="93" xml:id="d269fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</note> which was decoded yesterday. The
                    telegram was in the private cipher and is more or less garbled—however, <pb
                        facs="0376" n="308" xml:id="pg_308"/> I think that it is sufficiently clear
                    in expressing Mr. Page’s view as to the present situation.</p>
                <p>I give more weight to the telegram because he had, at the time of sending it, had
                    the advantage of consultation with Colonel House. Possibly you have received
                    from Colonel House telegrams which will throw light on Mr. Page’s point of view
                    and also that of the British Government. I hope that you will have had this
                    called to your attention before determining what course we should take with
                    regard to Germany.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
